{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Three squares of different areas are side by side. The middle square’s area is 16, and its opposite sides are each collinear with an adjacent square’s side. "}]},{"type":"text","text":"

"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"What is the area of the red quadrilateral?"}]},{"type":"text","text":"

"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"image","attrs":{"src":"/brilliantexport/brioche/uploads/V2cO3SBjl2-3-squares.svg?width=500"}}]}]}

discussion.body:
{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"image","attrs":{"src":"/brilliantexport/brioche/uploads/SbkSRlYKrk-b180721a.png?width=500"}},{"type":"text","text":"
Let the side length of the large square be "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"a"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":" and that of the small square be "},{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"b"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}},{"type":"text","text":". Then the area of the red region is:"}]},{"type":"text","text":"

"},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"katex","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\begin{aligned} A_{\text{quad}} & = \underbrace{a^2 + 16 + b^2}_{\text{Area of 3 squares}} - \underbrace{\frac {a(a+4)}2}_{\triangle_{\text{yellow}}} - \underbrace{\frac {a(a-4)}2}_{\triangle_{\text{blue}}} - \underbrace{\frac {b(b+4)}2}_{\triangle_{\text{green}}} + \underbrace{\frac {b(4-b)}2}_{\triangle_{\text{pink}}}
\\ & = a^2 + 16 + b^2 - \frac {a^2+4a+a^2-4a}2 - \frac {b^2+4b-4b+b^2}2
\\ & = a^2 + 16 + b^2 - a^2 - b^2
\\ & = \boxed{16}
\end{aligned}"}],"attrs":{"inline":true}}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"It is clear from the question that the area is expected to be unrelated to the size of the right and left squares. So imagine their sizes are both zero. It is immediately obvious you remaon exactly with the area of the middle square, which is 16."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"See all those guys doing all that math.  If this were a timed test, they would have wasted altogether too much time.  The quiz didn't offer "Not enough information to answer" as a choice, so one of those must be a solution.  Since they didn't specify the sizes of the other squares, then the solution doesn't depend on them, so make those sizes something convenient.  Make the larger square equal to the middle square and make the sides of the smaller square zero.  The solution is now quite obvious."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"There is no way to determine the size of the other  two squares.  So if the question makes sense then the answer must be the same whatever their sizes.  Assume they are 0.  The answer is 16."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The problem can be solved with deductive reasoning.  Since no measurements are given for the two squares adjacent to the known square, we can conclude the solution must work for all sizes of the adjacent squares.  By shrinking down each adjacent square to a point (area = 0) at opposite corners of the middle square the quadrilateral fills the middle square while occupying no area in the adjacent squares."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Since the measurements of the adjacent squares are arbitrary,  the  area of the quadrilateral will be equal for all measurements of the adjacent squares.  Then assume the adjacent squares to be equal to the mid square. Now the quadrilateral is a parallelogram with base =4 and height =4. Thus,  area of parallelogram =4*4=16"}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I multiplied 8 by 2 and got 16."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Since the problem did not specify the relative sizes of the three squares, the answer must be independent of their sizes. Taking them all to be the same size it becomes a simple application of the area of a trapezoid with known base and known altitude."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"If all square are the same, the answer is 16. So..."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Since the problem doesn't mention the size of the squares on the sides, it suggests that their sizes don't matter. So let them both be 4x4 as the central square is, then its obvious that the red quadrilateral is also 16 in area."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"What if, instead of squares ,it is circles. How different will the solution be?(after all area of circles is pi r square)"}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You can complete the middle square by using the red pieces"}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Just guessed it lol"}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Examine the limts.  If the large square has side length a and the small square has side length b then as a tends to 4 and b tends to 0 the diagram becomes a rectangle of size 8 horizontally by 4 vertically divided diagonally in half giving an area of the top half triangle of 16. Similarly, if a tends to 0 and b tends to zero the diagram becomes the central square of area 16."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Without loss of generality, the solution must be the same as the three squares become the same size and have the same area, and this remains the same as the area of the whole square in the middle."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"We don’t have sizes of the big and small square. It means that area of the red region doesn’t depend on those sizes. Make those squares equal to the middle square. Then the area of the red region is 4*4=16."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"As we are not given the areas of the two squares, there must be a general solution for all possible areas.  Condition is left square aligned with bottom of middle square, right square with top. General solution includes squares of side 0. If squares are of size 0, red shaded area becomes full middle square = 16."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"text","text":"




                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Consider that there is no information on the size of the outer squares, therefore, given the answers are numbers not equations, one can infer that it doesn't matter what size they are, the answer is invariant. So make the squares size zero. Then the top right of the quadrilateral becomes the top right of the central square, the bottom left becomes the bottom left of the central square, and the other two corners were already top left and bottom right of the square. The quadrilateral and square are now the same shape so have the same area."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



                            "}]}

